851
01:45:48,243 --> 01:45:49,388
[SPEAKER_51]: Thank you for joining us.

852
01:45:54,869 --> 01:45:59,815
[SPEAKER_26]: Good morning, everyone, and thank you, Councilmember Unisys, for bringing this to our chambers today.

853
01:46:00,176 --> 01:46:03,280
[SPEAKER_26]: And congratulations on being the madrina for this year's El Grito.

854
01:46:04,161 --> 01:46:21,282
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm honored to join you in celebration of Latino Heritage Month and to uplift two extraordinary individuals whose legacies embody this year's theme of viva la resistencia, reminding us that what we're going through, we've been through it, and we will supersede.

855
01:46:21,262 --> 01:46:25,586
[SPEAKER_26]: Carlos Montes is a pioneer Chicano activist and co-founder of the Brown Braids.

856
01:46:26,307 --> 01:46:31,792
[SPEAKER_26]: Francisco Letir is an internationally recognized muralist, illustrator, and poet.

857
01:46:32,453 --> 01:46:42,123
[SPEAKER_26]: Though their paths are different, their work has carried the same purpose, advancing justice, advancing our people, and ensuring that our stories are never erased.

858
01:46:42,823 --> 01:46:46,527
[SPEAKER_26]: Carlos represents the spirit of direct action and organizing.

859
01:46:46,507 --> 01:46:55,201
[SPEAKER_26]: From the East LA walkouts to the Chicano moratorium, he stood on the front lines demanding dignity and equality for generations of Chicanos and Latinos to come.

860
01:46:56,142 --> 01:47:02,693
[SPEAKER_26]: His courage shows us the impact the voices raise, barriers challenged, and communities united in struggle.

861
01:47:03,128 --> 01:47:05,231
[SPEAKER_26]: and a history that we can very much learn from.

862
01:47:05,292 --> 01:47:09,058
[SPEAKER_26]: Francisco shows us the power of art as resistance.

863
01:47:09,498 --> 01:47:15,609
[SPEAKER_26]: Through his murals, writing, and creative vision, he has turned art into living testaments of identity and resilience.

864
01:47:16,330 --> 01:47:18,794
[SPEAKER_26]: His work shows how art goes beyond expression.

865
01:47:19,475 --> 01:47:22,660
[SPEAKER_26]: It is preservation and a bridge between past and future.

866
01:47:22,680 --> 01:47:27,448
[SPEAKER_26]: There is no single way to properly resist.

867
01:47:27,867 --> 01:47:33,563
[SPEAKER_26]: There are those who march, organize, and mobilize, and those who paint, write, and tell our stories.

868
01:47:34,565 --> 01:47:40,662
[SPEAKER_26]: Both are necessary, both are powerful, and both deserve to be celebrated and acknowledged.

869
01:47:41,215 --> 01:47:46,203
[SPEAKER_26]: Because in the struggle for justice, there is a lane for each and every one of us to participate.

870
01:47:46,283 --> 01:47:50,449
[SPEAKER_26]: We should participate and bring to the table our talents in doing so.

871
01:47:51,431 --> 01:48:05,012
[SPEAKER_26]: So in a time when there's a target on us, it is important to know more than ever, to be proud and unapologetic of who we are, remember our past, learn from it, and propel forward.

