1076
02:05:24,414 --> 02:05:26,638
[SPEAKER_56]: So thank you so much and thank you for honoring him.

1077
02:05:28,930 --> 02:05:29,651
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you so much.

1078
02:05:29,911 --> 02:05:30,993
[SPEAKER_43]: Thank you so much, members.

1079
02:05:31,373 --> 02:05:38,483
[SPEAKER_43]: And thank you, Councilmembers Rodriguez, Padilla, Soto-Martinez, and the leader for our celebration this year.

1080
02:05:38,523 --> 02:05:40,866
[SPEAKER_43]: Councilmember Hernandez for bringing this.

1081
02:05:41,146 --> 02:05:50,078
[SPEAKER_43]: And I especially want to thank our council colleagues for centering and lifting in this celebration.

1082
02:05:51,239 --> 02:05:53,702
[SPEAKER_43]: the spirit of resistance and the spirit of struggle.

1083
02:05:54,203 --> 02:06:05,778
[SPEAKER_43]: Because this happens with Black History Month, with other celebrations where some people try to make it about beer or food or dancing or music, and all of those things are great.

1084
02:06:06,278 --> 02:06:17,112
[SPEAKER_43]: But we have these celebrations and commemorations to remind us of the struggle and how we got to the stage that we are now and how much further we have to go.

1085
02:06:17,092 --> 02:06:18,835
[SPEAKER_43]: And I couldn't be prouder.

1086
02:06:18,855 --> 02:06:25,328
[SPEAKER_43]: This is one of my proudest moments sitting up here to be chairing this meeting as we honor the great Carlos Montes.

1087
02:06:25,930 --> 02:06:29,597
[SPEAKER_43]: It's rare that you get to see your heroes in the flesh.

1088
02:06:30,198 --> 02:06:36,771
[SPEAKER_43]: I can remember watching you growing up as a young activist and then

1089
02:06:36,751 --> 02:06:46,627
[SPEAKER_43]: during my time at the Community Coalition where, you know, Karen Bass would say, yeah, I go back with Carlos, but you know, be careful out there.

1090
02:06:47,108 --> 02:06:48,530
[SPEAKER_43]: Be careful about getting locked up.

1091
02:06:48,590 --> 02:06:49,371
[SPEAKER_43]: Don't go too far.

1092
02:06:49,411 --> 02:06:50,293
[SPEAKER_43]: Don't take it too far.

1093
02:06:51,575 --> 02:07:02,472
[SPEAKER_43]: But I appreciate you because you embody the spirit of resistance when it's popular, but you also do it when it's not popular.

1094
02:07:02,570 --> 02:07:08,319
[SPEAKER_43]: when the media and society says, oh, we're having a good time.

1095
02:07:08,339 --> 02:07:09,701
[SPEAKER_43]: Why don't you go over there and be quiet?

1096
02:07:09,741 --> 02:07:12,205
[SPEAKER_43]: Stop bothering us about police brutality.

1097
02:07:12,225 --> 02:07:14,108
[SPEAKER_43]: Stop raising racism.

1098
02:07:14,148 --> 02:07:18,014
[SPEAKER_43]: We're trying to celebrate our progress, and here you are continuing to raise issues.

1099
02:07:18,034 --> 02:07:23,683
[SPEAKER_43]: So I thank you for sticking to the struggle, because it always comes back around.

1100
02:07:23,984 --> 02:07:35,526
[SPEAKER_43]: And right now we're in a moment where it's back around where I think the world looks at you and others and says, yeah, this is what he's been talking about the entire time.

1101
02:07:36,127 --> 02:07:44,743
[SPEAKER_43]: When racism goes from being dog whistle to just being whistle, which is what it is now, just straight up anti-Latino sentiment,

1102
02:07:44,723 --> 02:07:49,713
[SPEAKER_43]: unashamed, unembarrassed, immoral, and out front.

1103
02:07:50,574 --> 02:07:57,027
[SPEAKER_43]: And you've been an opponent of that when it's subtle, but also when it's direct.

1104
02:07:57,047 --> 02:08:00,814
[SPEAKER_43]: So thank you so much for everything that you've done, and we're proud to be able to honor you.

1105
02:08:01,074 --> 02:08:02,918
[SPEAKER_43]: And with that, Councilmember Anandas.

1106
02:08:04,012 --> 02:08:06,376
[SPEAKER_51]: Mr. President, we have one more person to bring up.

1107
02:08:07,137 --> 02:08:09,562
[SPEAKER_51]: And thank you, Carlos, for being here with us today.

1108
02:08:09,602 --> 02:08:16,975
[SPEAKER_51]: Latino resistance also lives in our art, murals, poetry, and storytelling that carry memory and connect us across generations.

1109
02:08:17,656 --> 02:08:26,391
[SPEAKER_51]: And Viva La Resistencia is not about how just we resist today, but it's about recognizing how we resisted in our past generations in different communities in different ways.

1110
02:08:26,962 --> 02:08:34,810
[SPEAKER_51]: Many of you have seen our Bridge Art Gallery exhibition, Viva La Resistencia, a celebration of Latino resistance and joy in a time of peril.

1111
02:08:35,350 --> 02:08:39,674
[SPEAKER_51]: That work would not have been possible without the partnership with the Department of Cultural Affairs.

1112
02:08:40,415 --> 02:08:47,222
[SPEAKER_51]: Today we have the privilege of unveiling the newest cover of the Latino Heritage Month edition of the DCA booklet and honoring the artists behind it.

1113
02:08:47,842 --> 02:08:56,631
[SPEAKER_51]: To introduce our second honoree, Francisco Letelier, please join me in welcoming Daniel Tarica, General Manager of the Department of Cultural Affairs.

1114
02:09:00,813 --> 02:09:02,495
[SPEAKER_74]: Thank you so much, Councilmember Hernandez.

1115
02:09:02,916 --> 02:09:08,362
[SPEAKER_74]: It's truly an honor to be here today to celebrate Latino Heritage Month on behalf of the Department of Cultural Affairs.

1116
02:09:09,143 --> 02:09:25,403
[SPEAKER_74]: In a time when pervasive discrimination continues to negatively impact our communities, lifting up and recognizing the city's rich cultural heritage and legacy through the arts is so important now more than it has been in recent history.

1117
02:09:25,383 --> 02:09:34,026
[SPEAKER_74]: Telling those stories and sharing experiences as a city's Latinx community is an important way for us to bring truth to power.

1118
02:09:34,782 --> 02:09:43,316
[SPEAKER_74]: Together, we honor the diverse Latinx communities that have shaped Los Angeles, our Southern California region, and across our nation for centuries.

1119
02:09:44,057 --> 02:09:58,140
[SPEAKER_74]: The community's impact is felt every day through its civic leaders, change makers, entrepreneurs and educators, caregivers and artisans, students and culture bearers, enriching our community in countless ways.

1120
02:09:58,120 --> 02:10:11,995
[SPEAKER_74]: This year, we continue the tradition by presenting the 2025 edition of the Latino Heritage Month Calendar and Cultural Guide that recognizes the accomplishments of our actors, our performers, our poets and our writers and our artists.

1121
02:10:12,856 --> 02:10:21,546
[SPEAKER_74]: It contains visual art and poetry from a wide selection of talented artists emerging and established, as well as many art exhibitions.

1122
02:10:22,454 --> 02:10:37,241
[SPEAKER_74]: The generations of artists and storytellers and culture bearers from communities across Latin America and here in Southern California that live here that have shaped our city and while their descendants carry that legacy forward every day through arts and culture as well as through business and civic leadership.

1123
02:10:37,822 --> 02:10:46,858
[SPEAKER_74]: The guide reflects the partnership of our many collaborators and I want to express our appreciation to our partners for the work of the offices of the mayor, the controller, the city attorney,

1124
02:10:47,125 --> 02:10:51,874
[SPEAKER_74]: City Council, and very much especially for the work of Councilmember Hernandez and her team.

1125
02:10:52,996 --> 02:11:05,559
[SPEAKER_74]: So as Councilmember Hernandez mentioned, in addition to the guide, we are also proud to support the work of the Bridge Gallery exhibition with Councilmember Hernandez and her team as well as Altura LA on the Viva La Resistencia.

1126
02:11:05,899 --> 02:11:08,965
[SPEAKER_74]: It is really a wonderful exhibition and I encourage you all to see it.

1127
02:11:09,451 --> 02:11:20,210
[SPEAKER_74]: So before we unveil the artwork of today's Latino Heritage Month calendar and cultural guide, I have the honor of introducing the artist who developed the guide's cover artwork.

1128
02:11:20,711 --> 02:11:27,342
[SPEAKER_74]: Francisco Letellier is an award-winning visual artist, graphic designer, illustrator, muralist, and poet.

1129
02:11:27,322 --> 02:11:30,569
[SPEAKER_74]: Letellier creates art that crosses disciplines and cultures.

1130
02:11:30,990 --> 02:11:39,368
[SPEAKER_74]: His work blends history with contemporary experiences with an emphasis on the social circumstances that affect our individuals and our communities.

1131
02:11:40,150 --> 02:11:43,457
[SPEAKER_74]: Mr. Letellier received a Grammy nomination for his work

1132
02:11:43,437 --> 02:11:46,162
[SPEAKER_74]: on musician Jackson Brown's World in Motion release.

1133
02:11:46,523 --> 02:11:51,492
[SPEAKER_74]: He has also been recognized through LA Art Corps, as well as through SPARC.

1134
02:11:52,253 --> 02:12:01,771
[SPEAKER_74]: And we also are very proud of his work, Todas Las Manos, at American University in Washington, DC, that was dedicated by Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.

1135
02:12:02,211 --> 02:12:05,277
[SPEAKER_74]: Please join me in welcoming el maestro Francisco Letillier.

1136
02:12:13,525 --> 02:12:33,948
[SPEAKER_39]: It's so nice to be here and for my artwork to be selected for this wonderful guiding calendar because when you get a chance to look through it, you'll see that we are a city rich in talent and artistic accomplishments.

1137
02:12:33,968 --> 02:12:36,411
[SPEAKER_39]: So I could be

1138
02:12:39,091 --> 02:12:41,876
[SPEAKER_39]: waiting for a long time to be on this cover.

1139
02:12:42,337 --> 02:12:44,621
[SPEAKER_39]: There are so many that deserve to be on it.

1140
02:12:45,121 --> 02:12:48,067
[SPEAKER_39]: But I just want to tell you a little bit about what inspired me.

1141
02:12:49,649 --> 02:12:53,556
[SPEAKER_39]: The illustration is called El Cantante, The Singer.

1142
02:12:54,498 --> 02:13:13,350
[SPEAKER_39]: And it's inspired by the vibrant culture that was repressed in Chile, where I was born, after the rise of the authoritarian dictatorship that overthrew democracy on September 11, 1973.

1143
02:13:14,596 --> 02:13:25,630
[SPEAKER_39]: It led to the imprisonment of thousands and the death of thousands, including my father and many people in my family, relatives and friends.

1144
02:13:27,252 --> 02:13:31,858
[SPEAKER_39]: Now through arts and culture, Chileans built solidarity and hope.

1145
02:13:32,579 --> 02:13:39,928
[SPEAKER_39]: They spread information and helped create the social movements that led back to democracy.

1146
02:13:41,309 --> 02:14:02,115
[SPEAKER_39]: Inspired by the diversity and knowledge held in the cultures of Los Angeles and across the Americas, my work recognizes travelers, the exchange of ideas, and it affirms our complexities, our celebrations, and our challenges.

1147
02:14:03,256 --> 02:14:04,718
[SPEAKER_39]: I'm grateful.

1148
02:14:05,002 --> 02:14:18,607
[SPEAKER_39]: to this council and the Department of Cultural Affairs for their ongoing efforts to defend and reimagine cultural heritage as a tool for progress and action.

1149
02:14:19,208 --> 02:14:21,752
[SPEAKER_39]: And today I want to say resistance.

1150
02:14:22,794 --> 02:14:26,381
[SPEAKER_39]: Que viva la ciudad de Los Angeles.

1151
02:14:27,002 --> 02:14:27,583
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you.

1152
02:14:34,229 --> 02:15:02,835
[SPEAKER_51]: On behalf of the city of LA we want to recognize Francisco let's yeah, we'll do a picture because we know folks around Thank you, thank you

1153
02:15:03,220 --> 02:15:08,550
[SPEAKER_51]: We want to recognize you for your extraordinary contributions, Francisco, to the arts and your shared struggle for justice.

1154
02:15:09,091 --> 02:15:10,273
[SPEAKER_51]: And I want to point something out.

1155
02:15:10,834 --> 02:15:15,102
[SPEAKER_51]: We're going through authoritarianism, what feels like a takeover here in this country.

1156
02:15:15,944 --> 02:15:19,851
[SPEAKER_51]: And oftentimes, I know I've said this, it's like, oh, we don't have a playbook.

1157
02:15:20,412 --> 02:15:22,917
[SPEAKER_51]: What to do?

1158
02:15:22,897 --> 02:15:26,862
[SPEAKER_51]: Places like Chile that have survived authoritarianism have playbooks.

1159
02:15:27,323 --> 02:15:32,069
[SPEAKER_51]: They have showed us what it takes to build community power to survive moments like these.

1160
02:15:32,570 --> 02:15:34,472
[SPEAKER_51]: So I appreciate you, Francisco, for lifting that up.

1161
02:15:35,373 --> 02:15:39,879
[SPEAKER_51]: Colleagues, what you've seen today is that Latino resistance is not just about protest.

1162
02:15:40,220 --> 02:15:41,361
[SPEAKER_51]: It's also about creation.

1163
02:15:41,462 --> 02:15:48,651
[SPEAKER_51]: It's about building a world where our stories, our struggles, and our joy are reflected back to us in art, in history, and community.

1164
02:15:48,631 --> 02:15:56,312
[SPEAKER_51]: Carlos Montes and Francisco Letelier show us two sides of the same coin, the power of action and the power of imagination.

1165
02:15:57,727 --> 02:16:04,196
[SPEAKER_51]: That is the spirit of Latino Heritage Month, honoring our past, fighting for our future, and celebrating the beauty and resilience of our people.

1166
02:16:04,897 --> 02:16:13,649
[SPEAKER_51]: I'm so proud to officially recognize this month as Latino Heritage Month on behalf of the city of Los Angeles, and I hope to see each and every one of you tomorrow at El Grito celebrating with us.

1167
02:16:14,310 --> 02:16:19,718
[SPEAKER_51]: Colleagues, now please join me in the unveiling of our Latino Heritage Book this year.

1168
02:16:28,118 --> 02:16:28,519
[SPEAKER_51]: Thank you.

1169
02:16:28,740 --> 02:16:29,822
[SPEAKER_51]: Que viva la resistencia.

